1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:12,000
Where do you roll?

3
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:18,000
Okay.

4
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:22,000
Today is Saturday March 9, 2013.

5
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:29,000
My name is Willie Griffin and I am a research associate with the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

6
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:38,000
I am with videographer John Bishop and Albany Georgia on the campus of Albany State University to conduct an interview for the Civil Rights History Project,

7
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:46,000
which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

8
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:49,000
We are here today with Mr. Sam Young, Jr.

9
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:55,000
Thank you so much for being here Mr. Young and agreeing to share your story with us on the Civil Rights History Project.

10
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:56,000
Thank you.

11
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:05,000
All right. So I just want to begin first off by having you stay to full name and tell when and where to go.

12
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:09,000
Okay. My name is Sam Young, Jr.

13
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:19,000
And I was born in Worth County, Sylvester, Georgia.

14
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:22,000
March 13, 1950.

15
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:24,000
Okay. March 13, 1950.

16
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:34,000
So what was it like growing up in 1950, you were right on the cusp of the Brown vs. Board of Education.

17
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:39,000
What else is going on in the civil rights movement?

18
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:52,000
In the 1950s growing up, I was very aware of certain issues like the Board of Education thing.

19
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:58,000
And my father, he was very political and he always kept us abreast on different issues.

20
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:04,000
But I did not understand what that was all about during when he was telling me about it.

21
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:05,000
What was your father's name?

22
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:07,000
About the Board of Education.

23
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:10,000
Your father's name was Sam Young, Jr.

24
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:13,000
Right, right. He was Sam Young, Jr.

25
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:19,000
And he was very influential in the political scene.

26
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:25,000
And he always kept us abreast about different political issues that were going on around us.

27
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:26,000
Okay.

28
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:31,000
And he made us watch the news every day.

29
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:44,000
And when I really understood my after I became older and had some of the issues faced me, you know, head on.

30
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:51,000
And then I understood a lot of things that he would be speaking of.

31
00:02:51,000 --> 00:03:00,000
So like for example, in Worth County, did you experience any of the signs of racism or...

32
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:02,000
Oh, growing up in Worth County?

33
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:08,000
Yes, especially during our school integration.

34
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:09,000
Okay.

35
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:15,000
You know, because when I went to, at that time, it was Freedom of Choice.

36
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:25,000
You know, you had, you know, if you wanted to go, you know, that was one of the, I guess, one of the things that they did to keep people from actually...

37
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:26,000
Right.

38
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:33,000
So you had the opportunity to go to a white school if you did, but you could remain in a all black school if you wanted to.

39
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:34,000
Right.

40
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:35,000
Okay.

41
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:40,000
And lots of my friends, you know, they did exactly that.

42
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:52,000
But I chose to go to the, with Freedom of Choice, things chose to go to the other schools, the white schools.

43
00:03:52,000 --> 00:04:02,000
And when I started school, we, our schools were out with our churches in Worth County.

44
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:07,000
And we were walked every day back and forth, you know, to school.

45
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:12,000
And the school buses would come by.

46
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:24,000
And as I remember, the children, you know, what hang the heads out of the window, when they're calling us, or racial names and all that.

47
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:36,000
But we, the bus would always meet at the paths in the woods were always clear" when we got out of school, we would always be exactly about the same place.

48
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:42,000
And you know, little kids, you know, when somebody's messing with you, you know, we threw rocks at the bus, you know.

49
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:44,000
I mean, that's what we did.

50
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:49,000
And the bus driver would put the lights on, you know, brake lights.

51
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:50,000
We see the brake lights come out.

52
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:51,000
Right.

53
00:04:51,000 --> 00:05:02,000
And back in those days, they were during what they called turpentine time, you know, where they get the bus straight to the tree and get the, what they call gum.

54
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:05,000
And they would make a lot of our products out of that.

55
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:09,000
And the, the, the, the, the, the paths in the woods were always clear".

56
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:14,000
And we just try to get through with, maybe they'd never be able to catch them.

57
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:29,000
You know, and I, when I went to school, when we, when they did build schools in Worse County, my father said that I could not read.

58
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:36,000
And I had a sister coming into the first grade, the same time, at that same time.

59
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:38,000
I support them in the second grade.

60
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:43,000
And we went through school together, you know.

61
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:46,000
And everybody thought we were twins, but we're not.

62
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:50,000
My father kept me back because he said I could not read.

63
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:57,000
And I'm very glad that he did that because I probably could look at some of my grandchildren sometimes.

64
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:04,000
And even my own kids, you know, I knew they, they would not qualify, you know, to read.

65
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:07,000
And I'm glad he cared about that.

66
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:13,000
And I had the kind of teachers that you, you, you didn't escape.

67
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:14,000
There was no net.

68
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:16,000
You had to get your lesson.

69
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:20,000
Right. You know, and, and you had to, you, there was no cheating.

70
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:22,000
And you weren't just going to disappear in the back of the class.

71
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:23,000
Oh, no.

72
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:24,000
That was not going to happen.

73
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:33,000
And once I remember, I, I always tell my grandkids this story, you know, about trying to cheat.

74
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:37,000
I was caught sitting on a spelling book.

75
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:43,000
And the teacher came back to me, she said, young, are you cheating?

76
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:45,000
And I said, no.

77
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:47,000
She said, well, stand up.

78
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:50,000
And when I stood up, you know, the spelling book right there.

79
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:52,000
And I, and she spanked me.

80
00:06:52,000 --> 00:07:02,000
And then I remember, you know, getting, you know, I guess, you know, upset and say, well, you know, I'm going to tell my father, you know, I'm going to tell my mother.

81
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:05,000
And at those days, you know, she said, come on, let's go.

82
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:09,000
I'll take you to her because we can see who's right.

83
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:13,000
I really didn't want that to happen.

84
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:15,000
You're a posture.

85
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:19,000
But that's that's some of the things that happen.

86
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:35,000
And when the schools integrated, you know, I'm under the impression that, you know, okay, the white people are way smarter.

87
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:43,000
I'm going into with this expectation, you know, and I had her.

88
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:54,000
It was a very awakening experience, you know, and then when you let one other thing that my parents told me, you never follow the crowd.

89
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:59,000
You were born and individual and you would die and individually.

90
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:03,000
And that's one that I do that even today.

91
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:16,000
Even though some issues might be, you know, if I decide to go along, is that we, if just that's a universal thing, that everything is, you know, good.

92
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:19,000
And I go along, but if I got some issues with it, I would not do it.

93
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:22,000
And just because of the group.

94
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:35,000
And we had several incidents of racist, racial things to happen.

95
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:47,000
They came out to our church, some kids, you know, just basically kids doing things, you know, and they, they are painted the front of our church.

96
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:52,000
It's the same church that I grew up at and you know, went to school and all that.

97
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:54,000
What was the name of the church?

98
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:58,000
Blue spraying Baptist church in Worth Church.

99
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:00,000
Okay.

100
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:01,000
Okay.

101
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:04,000
And so they painted some things on it.

102
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:11,000
The church black and said written that this is the devil's den or something of that.

103
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:17,000
But we found out there was one of the local vendors, some that did it.

104
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:27,000
And he made him go back out and repaint the whole thing, you know, because of what he had did.

105
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:50,000
And we had some other incidents, you know, matter of fact, my cousins, two of my cousins were taken into custody at Worth County High School because she, she and the white guy got into it and she beat him.

106
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:58,000
They came and arrested her, right off the school bus and they took them, brought them over. They went to Worth County.

107
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:04,000
They brought them over to Albany at the Youth Detention Center here.

108
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:12,000
And the sheriff would not tell my aunt where those kids were.

109
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:15,000
Was this pressure? Was this still a pressure in Albany?

110
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:16,000
No, no, this was.

111
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:18,000
Oh, the sheriff was.

112
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:22,000
I think it was at that time, I believe it was a pressure. Well, it was about to one day.

113
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:23,000
Okay.

114
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:25,000
I'm not sure what they were related.

115
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:35,000
But at the time, Attorney C.B. King was a very prominent black lawyer here.

116
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:37,000
And they are.

117
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:46,000
It was only the children were out of place for three days before the sheriff would tell.

118
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:52,000
He would not, my aunt went down to the, they would not tell her where her children were.

119
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:55,000
Your cousins can't be any more than 14, maybe, maybe?

120
00:10:55,000 --> 00:10:57,000
Somewhere in that neighborhood.

121
00:10:57,000 --> 00:11:02,000
And they took her to those two kids.

122
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:09,000
And C.B. threatened to have the sheriff arrested.

123
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:15,000
And at that point, he told whether the children were, and they were over here in Albany.

124
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:22,000
But beforehand, beforehand, they would not release the location of whether the children were.

125
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:28,000
And it was kind of scary because we were young.

126
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:35,000
And when somebody takes a, some part of your family, and nobody's telling you where they are,

127
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:44,000
and understanding some of the issues that would black people going on all over the country, especially in the South,

128
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:49,000
we were some of the children that, they might be, you know, disincent of something.

129
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:51,000
And they're not just the police.

130
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:52,000
Yeah.

131
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:55,000
So that was that.

132
00:11:55,000 --> 00:12:04,000
And I have seen a lot, not seen, but I have been in the presence of a lot of things.

133
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:14,000
I even have some people that were shot because they were trying to break up a fight.

134
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:22,000
And that was a guy that came out and just, you know, shot him.

135
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:27,000
You know, just because, you know, I guess, you know, he was the white guy.

136
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:29,000
And you were a school age at this time?

137
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:32,000
I was a school age, you know, you're doing the time right.

138
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:34,000
All these things are happening.

139
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:36,000
Lots of things happen.

140
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:43,000
Then once, you know, I remember my father was a Sunday school teacher also.

141
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:52,000
And I remember one of the deacons, one of my, you know, kids we all grew up in our trade family.

142
00:12:52,000 --> 00:12:57,000
And he came to work, not to work, but to have been to work.

143
00:12:57,000 --> 00:13:05,000
And he got shot.

144
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:12,000
The guy that he was working for.

145
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:20,000
The son of that, his employee, wanted him to call him.

146
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:24,000
This man was probably three times his son because he was a teenager.

147
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:29,000
But he wanted him to call him the young guy wanted him to call him Mr.

148
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:32,000
So he said, no, I'm not going to call you Mr.

149
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:39,000
And so the father, he went to the father and told the father about it.

150
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:51,000
And the father without asking the, my friend's nose father, anything about he just came out with his shotgun.

151
00:13:51,000 --> 00:13:52,000
Wow.

152
00:13:52,000 --> 00:14:04,000
And the only reason, I always remember, I couldn't understand how another human being could do such things to one another.

153
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:06,000
But he got shot.

154
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:15,000
And the only reason that he didn't get blinded or killed was he threw his hands up, you know, as a shield.

155
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:21,000
And I remember in our Sunday school, he was telling about the story.

156
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:30,000
And you know, the buckshot, you know, he had all the, you know, the pellets and stuff, where they, you know, penetrated skin and in his face, you know.

157
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:32,000
So he would have been blinded.

158
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:33,000
He was aiming for his head.

159
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:34,000
Yeah.

160
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:39,000
And he just, he was some turbotimes.

161
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:42,000
He was some turbotimes.

162
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:49,000
And things may have changed.

163
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:53,000
And they may not have taken.

164
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:56,000
Do you remember this guy's name and all of them who got shot?

165
00:14:56,000 --> 00:14:58,000
His name was Albert Gill.

166
00:14:58,000 --> 00:14:59,000
Albert Gill.

167
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:00,000
Oh, the one that got shot?

168
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:01,000
Yeah.

169
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:03,000
Oh, no, his name was CT Rockwell.

170
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:04,000
CT Rockwell.

171
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:06,000
And Albert Gill was who?

172
00:15:06,000 --> 00:15:07,000
The shooter.

173
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:08,000
Okay.

174
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:09,000
No, right.

175
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:10,000
Yeah.

176
00:15:10,000 --> 00:15:11,000
Yeah.

177
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:28,000
But sometimes, you know, I think back, I have some embedded hatred for, you know, sometimes.

178
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:34,000
But as I grow older, I look at things.

179
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:45,000
And even though there was some, a lot of things, you know, directed, you know, the racial thing directed towards my father,

180
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:48,000
because they were like, they were black land on us.

181
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:49,000
Right.

182
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:53,000
And loans were foreclosed, you know, everything, you know.

183
00:15:53,000 --> 00:16:03,000
And I remember there was a local white grocer that he also had a hardware store.

184
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:10,000
And he extended my father a line of credit, you know, to farm with.

185
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:16,000
And that's how we made it through those times.

186
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:24,000
And we, he, my father, ran and I profit to him for years.

187
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:26,000
I never understood it.

188
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:38,000
But after he quit farming, you know, but see, performing for young black men, you know, and for the farm, you know, the land in order to be passed on to the black people.

189
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:45,000
There was nothing, you know, there was no, and then I look at now, even the farmers around us.

190
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:53,000
And their kids, generations of them, you know, the land and the farming business has passed on and on on to them.

191
00:16:53,000 --> 00:16:57,000
But, you know, there was no such thing for black people.

192
00:16:57,000 --> 00:17:14,000
And just recently, I guess, there are a lot of opportunities, you know, after the, the, the, oh man, the ASCS (Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation Service) office of,

193
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:18,000
they got to, they changed it to Farm Service Agency now.

194
00:17:18,000 --> 00:17:25,000
And there's a lot of things out there that are, you know, good for, you know, young black farmers.

195
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:31,000
But I think, you know, we went through an era where, you know, farm was work.

196
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:34,000
We don't, we don't want to put out that camera.

197
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:36,000
And you learned it from your father.

198
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:38,000
Right. I grew up on the farm.

199
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:39,000
Okay. Right.

200
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:41,000
And I was up, what were some of the things you planted?

201
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:48,000
I was planted cotton, corn, peanuts, vegetables, squash, butter beans, peas, okra.

202
00:17:48,000 --> 00:17:54,000
And then I was, we were the one, our children, you know, I'm from a large family.

203
00:17:54,000 --> 00:17:57,000
And how many brothers and sisters?

204
00:17:57,000 --> 00:18:02,000
I have 10 sisters. I had 10 sisters and they were seven brothers.

205
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:13,000
And I, I see, when I think about it, you know, we had the large family because we were going to be the ones

206
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:20,000
to, to together the crops and everything, which was bad because I learned a lot of experiences about work.

207
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:28,000
You know, and I was the oldest son and I had two sisters that were older than I am.

208
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:33,000
And we all graduated from our schools and were in our, in our county.

209
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:42,000
You know, when the odds were, well, basically, you know, I guess, you know, you're receiving a pretty good education.

210
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:45,000
I just, you know, I'm receiving a diploma.

211
00:18:45,000 --> 00:18:46,000
Yeah.

212
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:47,000
Yeah.

213
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:52,000
And I graduated, I was the only in 1968.

214
00:18:52,000 --> 00:18:55,000
It was when I graduated.

215
00:18:56,000 --> 00:19:07,000
And I think as I remember, I might have been the only, like, male, you know, in that group.

216
00:19:07,000 --> 00:19:13,000
It's a class, you know, it's probably about four or five, like, ladies.

217
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:16,000
What was the name of the school of high school you graduated from?

218
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:20,000
Our Worth County High School in Sylvester, Georgia.

219
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:23,000
So, and you graduated in 1968.

220
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:24,000
Sixth grade.

221
00:19:24,000 --> 00:19:25,000
Sixth grade.

222
00:19:25,000 --> 00:19:27,000
Sixth grade, that was a, really critical time.

223
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:30,000
Sixth grade, I suppose, very, very critical.

